<paragraph id="A44DAF3E9D43FFE9FEEEF912FBC7F91A" blockId="7.[264,1324,284,1876]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Etymology. The species name, 
<taxonomicName id="63F2D4BD9D43FFE9FD71F912FCD5F975" box="[679,786,1690,1715]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apoticius">
<emphasis id="9686732C9D43FFE9FD71F912FCD5F975" box="[679,786,1690,1715]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">apoticius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a combination of the 
<typeStatus id="7B49119C9D43FFE9FBEEF912FBADF972" box="[1080,1130,1690,1716]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">type</typeStatus>
locality (Mount Apo) and the latin 
<emphasis id="9686732C9D43FFE9FE32F94AFDECF91D" box="[484,555,1730,1755]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">iticius</emphasis>
(belonging to). The gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A44DAF3E9D43FFE6FEEEF962FEBAFE98" blockId="7.[264,1324,284,1876]" lastBlockId="8.[264,1323,284,350]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName id="63F2D4BD9D43FFE9FE67F962FD01F8C5" box="[433,710,1770,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apoticius">
<emphasis id="9686732C9D43FFE9FE67F962FD01F8C5" box="[433,710,1770,1795]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Pygommatius apoticius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the combined characters of the male terminalia (
<figureCitation id="3CC9B3BB9D43FFE9FE05F89AFD95F8EA" box="[467,594,1810,1836]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs. 
<number id="123ABD199D43FFE9FDCEF89AFD95F8EA" box="[536,594,1810,1836]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="6.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="1.0">1–11</number>
</figureCitation>
), especially the shape of the epandrium, i.e. trilobed apex of the dorsal branch, claw­like apex of the middle branch, and the hooked ventral branch and caninelike apex of the gonostylus. Also, it differs from 
<taxonomicName id="63F2D4BD9D4CFFE6FC43FE94FB45FEF0" authority="Oldroyd" authorityName="Oldroyd" box="[917,1154,284,310]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hypnus">
<emphasis id="9686732C9D4CFFE6FC43FE94FBC2FEF3" box="[917,1029,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">P. hypnus</emphasis>
(Oldroyd)
</taxonomicName>
by the yellow fore coxa.
</paragraph>
